attributes.title: Eye Movement Meaning
attributes.description: In visual world eye tracking paradigms employing referential tasks, a common linking assumption is that the proportion of looks to a referent within a window of interest reflects the degree of belief that that referent is the intended one. However, this linking assumption has rarely been tested. We follow the methodology employed by Qing, Lassiter, & Degen 2018, who tested the assumption on an experimental semantics eye movement dataset elicited by Leffel et al. We implement Experiment 3 from Sun & Breheny 2019 using an incremental decision task to elicit explicit belief distributions, and test to what extent these explicit beliefs are predictive of the eye movement data they collected.

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

other.value: We will subsequently run a free production study that aims to establish the probabilities of the linguistic stimuli used in the original experiment. Previous work (Qing et al 2018) provides some evidence that the correlation between explicit beliefs in an incremental decision task and implicit beliefs as expressed in eye movements is greater when the observed linguistic stimulus is not entirely unlikely.

analyses.value: For each unique combination of condition, determiner, set size, and time window, we will compute the proportion of looks from Sun & Breheny 2019 to each of the four referents in the display.  For each of these unique combinations, we will also compute the proportion of clicks to each of the four referents in the display. We will analyze whether click proportions are a significant predictor of look proportions.

dependent.value: Referent selections at 4 different points in time during the unfolding utterance: the prior window, the gender window, the quantifier window, and the disambiguating noun window, in sentences like “Click on the | girl with | some of | Susan’s apples”.

conditions.value: We will completely reproduce Sun & Breheny Experiment 3, including all of their materials and assignment processes. Each participant will be randomly assigned to one of three lists of experimental trials.

hypothesis.value: This study fulfills two purposes. First, we investigate if the linking assumption described above is warranted by comparing eye-tracking data with data about participants’ beliefs about intended referents. Second, we replicate Sun & Breheny 2019 Experiment 3 using an incremental decision task instead of an eye-movement paradigm.

attributes.title: Personality and Social Claims
attributes.description: In this study, we aim to measure perception and cognitive processing of conventional or socially posited entities, such as institutional roles or national borders.

q2.value:
H1: Viewing an animated synchronous dance will result in a blurring of perceived social roles, leading to a reduced difference between imputed social status rankings of kings and commoners after viewing a synchronous dance, as opposed to a non-synchronous dance.
H1a: Imputed differences in rank will be most pronounced in the non-motion condition, in which the king not taking part in the dance at all, as this visual distinction between the king and the commoners will draw more attention to differences between social roles. We expect that participants who view asynchronous dance will also show larger differences in ranking than the non-motion condition, as there will be some blurring in social roles in comparison to the non-motion condition. We expect the least imputed differences in rank in the synchrony condition, since shared, synchronized movement should make role differences less salient between characters. Essentially, we predict that imputed differences for non-motion > imputed difference in asynchronous > imputed differences in synchronous dance.

H2: Because viewing synchronous dances will blur social roles and social roles are a type of subjective social convention (“institutional facts” rather than “brute facts”; Searle 1995), subjective items on our scale will be seen as more subjective for participants who have viewed to the synchronous dance animation. We do not expect either category of objective items to vary by condition, with the caveat that it may be possible, as an effect was seen for cynicism’s correlation with these two categories in the pilot study.

H3: Real-world items will clearly delineate into categories of subjective, objective physical items, and objective person-related items, just as the fictional items did initially in our pilot study.
H3a: We expect that in this study, both sets of items will rate similarly on the objectivity-subjectivity scale.

H4: We predict that there will be several covariates associated with either higher or lower subjectivity ratings of our items, as listed below.
H4a: In accordance with our pilot study results, we expect that items will be rated more subjectively in people who show higher cynicism. In our pilot study, we observed that this effect was due to objective items being rated more subjectively. We would expect the same pattern here, though our theoretical framework would better explain subjectively rated items being rated as more subjective in those with higher cynicism.
H4b: In terms of OCEAN personality traits, we expect the openness to experience trait to be most relevant in terms of predicting subjectivity ratings. We predict that those with higher openness to novel experiences would be more willing to question the objectivity of items, and therefore will rate subjective items more subjectively. While both classes of objective items could differ as they did with cynicism in our pilot study, we do not predict these ratings to vary as a function of personality.
H4c: In terms of analytical style as measured by the Triad Task, we expect that those with more abstract thinking styles will be more questioning of subjective items, and therefore will rate subjective items more subjectively. Again, we expect the difference in ratings to occur in subjective items, rather than in either category of objective items.
H4d: We expect that those who endorse more individualistic (“liberating”) morals will see social institutions as less important, and therefore will rate subjective items more subjectively. Conversely, we expect that those who endorse binding morals will view subjective items more objectively. We expect no difference in ratings of objective items.
H4e: Past negativity (negative past experiences, especially during childhood) may be more predictive of cynicism and therefore questioning of social claims, and therefore may predict more subjective ratings of subjective items. In contrast, past positivity may predict more objective ratings of subjective items. We expect no difference in ratings of objective items.
H4f: For many of our demographics, we expect that exposure to normative situations in which institutionalized social roles are central throughout a lifetime may lead to increased acceptance of social institutions, and therefore subjective items will be rated more objectively. This would apply to sports participation, religion’s importance in one’s life, and marriage. We do not expect ratings of objective items to differ.
H4g: For some of the demographic variables, we expect certain positions to be associated with questioning and skepticism of social roles and institutional claims, and therefore more subjective rankings of subjective items: education, younger age, and liberal political leanings. We do not expect a difference in ratings of objective items.
H4h: We do not have a prediction for music participation or socioeconomic status’s effects on subjectivity items. Because we expect synchrony – a major element of music participation – to involve diffusing of roles in a musical group, but we also expect formal musical education and participation to be associated with accepting social structures, there may be conflicting effects, making it difficult to predict whether music will have a positive or negative effect on ratings of subjectivity. Similarly, while those with lower socioeconomic status may have more reason to question social institutions, they also tend to be more socially conservative (Jost, 2017), and so may not actually endorse views skeptical of institutions.

question.value:
We will provide a fictional story prompt with both subjective and objective elements (ex.: an international boundary versus a river), and ask participants to rate items on a scale from objective to subjective. We will also measure potential correlates of this subjectivity scale, such as cynicism, morals, positivity towards the past, cognitive style, personality, and demographics. These subjectivity ratings will also be compared to subjectivity ratings for real-world items. In an additional manipulation, a short animation of a dance will be shown in which two of the dancers are “commoners” (simple stick figures) and one figure is a “king” (a stick figure with a large, conspicuous crown). The dance animation will have three conditions: 1) totally synchronized dance (all three stick figures are in time-locked entrainment); 2) asynchronous, “detuned” dance (the king dances the same moves as the commoners, but on a different frequency and out of phase); 3) non-motion (the king stands immobile while the commoners dance). This manipulation is aimed at determining whether viewing synchronous dances will blur the lines between socially constructed roles, as opposed to viewing non-synchronous dances. To measure this, participants will be asked to spatially rank the social status of conventionally high-status roles (kings) and low-status roles (commoners) after viewing the animation, and the difference between rankings on a 9-point vertical scale will be observed. 

This study is mixed design, with most of our analysis relying on between-subject design.

Subjects will first read the fictional prompt, followed by the dance animation prime. Then subjects will rate subjectivity of fictional, and then real world items. Afterwards, subjects will rate social standing of kings and commoners. Following that, we will measure all of our non-demographic, potential correlates of the king ranking scale. Lastly, we will record demographic information.

question.value:
We will recruit subjects via Prolific, an online platform similar to Amazon's Mturk program, on which subjects can participate in studies and be paid. Subjects who participate through Prolific will be redirected to our Qualtrics link to participate in the study. We will require subjects to be at least 18 years of age and be able to read and understand the English language. Prolific will screen for this, and we will screen one more time in our study that subjects meet these requirements. A final exclusion criteria will be any subjects who took part in our pilot study.

Data collection will happen throughout April 2020, until we reach our desired subject number of 500. Subjects will be paid £3.15 for completing the survey.

A confirmatory factor analysis will be performed on both the real world and fictional items, in order to confirm that the items fit in the three factor model.

Analyses for H1: We will carry out a one-way ANOVA to determine whether the three groups showed significant differences, with social status difference rankings as the dependent variable. Post-hoc tests will determine differences between each pair of groups. 
IV: 1 (a,b,c)
DV: 8

Analyses for H2: We will carry out a separate one-way ANOVA for each dependent variable (2 through 7) to determine whether the three groups showed significant differences, with subjectivity ratings as the dependent variable. Post-hoc tests will determine differences between each pair of groups.
IV: 1 (a,b,c)
DV: 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7

Analyses for H3: We will perform a separate confirmatory factor analysis to analyze each set of items (fictional and real-world). We expect that both the real world and fictional items will easily fit into three categories of objective-physical items, objective person-related items, and subjective items.
Indicator Variables: 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7

Analyses for H4: For these analyses, we will carry out a multiple regression with subjectivity of each subgroup of items (variables 2-7) as the dependent variables, including independent variables 8-32 as possible sources of variability in the dependent variables.

IV: 8-32
DV: 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7

attributes.title: Elevating dental training to reduce HPV-related oropharyngeal cancer incidence rates
attributes.description:
Background. Often, the first signs of oropharyngeal cancer (OPC), particularly Human papillomavirus infection (HPV)-related OPC, can be detected during a head and neck examination performed by an oral health care provider. Since the incidence of HPV-related OPC has increased significantly, it has become more important that these providers are familiar with the presenting signs and symptoms of OPC and its relation to HPV.  Furthermore dentists should be empowered to encourage vaccination against HPV, perform oral screenings, and educate patients around the risk factors for HPV-related OPC.  
Rationale. In accordance with Commission on Dental Accreditation (CODA), standards for pre-doctoral dental education programs state that dental graduates should be prepared to: screen and assess for head and neck cancer, health promotion and disease prevention, (2-24) and have the interpersonal and communications skills to function successfully in a multicultural work environment (2-17).  Therefore, we conducted a comprehensive review of the literature to examine pre-doctoral dental students’ 1) awareness of the connection between OPC and HPV 2) readiness to assess OPC 3) delivery of patient education about OPC and its relation to HPV and 4) identify existing OPC and HPV training in the curricula.

summary.value:
Background. Often, the first signs of oropharyngeal cancer (OPC), particularly Human papillomavirus infection (HPV)-related OPC, can be detected during a head and neck examination performed by an oral health care provider. Since the incidence of HPV-related OPC has increased significantly, it has become more important that these providers are familiar with the presenting signs and symptoms of OPC and its relation to HPV.  Furthermore dentists should be empowered to encourage vaccination against HPV, perform oral screenings, and educate patients around the risk factors for HPV-related OPC.  
Rationale. In accordance with Commission on Dental Accreditation (CODA), standards for pre-doctoral dental education programs state that dental graduates should be prepared to: screen and assess for head and neck cancer, health promotion and disease prevention, (2-24) and have the interpersonal and communications skills to function successfully in a multicultural work environment (2-17).  Therefore, we conducted a comprehensive review of the literature to examine pre-doctoral dental students’ 1) awareness of the connection between OPC and HPV 2) readiness to assess OPC 3) delivery of patient education about OPC and its relation to HPV and 4) identify existing OPC and HPV training in the curricula.
Data Collection. A structured search of Medline (PubMed), Medline (Ovid), Scopus, ERIC, Cumulative Index for Nursing and Allied Health (EBSCO), Academic search Premier (EBSCO), and Dissertations and Theses (Proquest). The search for literature included dates of database inception through February 2019. **Our search strategy and study selection process is further explained using a modified PRISMA Flow Diagram (not pictured).
Data Analysis. Out of 360 articles, 39 were eligible for review and assessment. Inclusion criteria: articles published in English, discussed pre-doctoral dental student training, awareness, competency for risk assessment, and curriculum content for OPC and its relation to HPV.  Reviewers independently reviewed abstracts, selected articles for inclusion and extracted data.  Discrepancies among reviewers were resolved by consensus characterization.  
Results. In this preliminary study we focused on mapping the nature and volume of the existing literature rather than an answer to a question; but these findings present a significant educational training opportunity for dental students with respect to their understanding and detection of OPC and HPV.  We identified 12 studies that examined discussed pre-doctoral dental student training, awareness, competency for risk assessment, and curriculum content for OPC and its relation to HPV. Five studies described pre-doctoral dental students’ ability to deliver patient education about OPC and its relation to HPV.  Most studies involved the examination of pre-doctoral dental students’ awareness of HPV and OPC connection (n=12) and readiness to assess risks for OPC (n=11).  Studies that described content developed or existing content utilized within their programs were rare (n=3) and but did demonstrate adoptions of curriculum content within pre-doctoral training.  Although the majority of publications within this study state the need for HPV and OPC training and curriculum inclusion for pre-doctoral dental students, there is limited published literature on this content. Future analysis should include survey assessment of pre-doctoral dental training programs efforts for enhancing student efficacy and awareness for HPV-related OPC.
Conclusions. Future dental curricula should include understanding risks for HPV and OPC, conducting relevant assessments for OPC and HPV risks and behaviors, communication techniques in patient health education as well as training to empower preceptors and/or clinical faculty. Implementation of curricula with such learning competencies presents a unique opportunity to prepare a dental workforce to increase detection of OPC, awareness of HPV-related oropharyngeal cancer and increase vaccination rates against HPV.

registration_responses.summary:
Background. Often, the first signs of oropharyngeal cancer (OPC), particularly Human papillomavirus infection (HPV)-related OPC, can be detected during a head and neck examination performed by an oral health care provider. Since the incidence of HPV-related OPC has increased significantly, it has become more important that these providers are familiar with the presenting signs and symptoms of OPC and its relation to HPV.  Furthermore dentists should be empowered to encourage vaccination against HPV, perform oral screenings, and educate patients around the risk factors for HPV-related OPC.  
Rationale. In accordance with Commission on Dental Accreditation (CODA), standards for pre-doctoral dental education programs state that dental graduates should be prepared to: screen and assess for head and neck cancer, health promotion and disease prevention, (2-24) and have the interpersonal and communications skills to function successfully in a multicultural work environment (2-17).  Therefore, we conducted a comprehensive review of the literature to examine pre-doctoral dental students’ 1) awareness of the connection between OPC and HPV 2) readiness to assess OPC 3) delivery of patient education about OPC and its relation to HPV and 4) identify existing OPC and HPV training in the curricula.
Data Collection. A structured search of Medline (PubMed), Medline (Ovid), Scopus, ERIC, Cumulative Index for Nursing and Allied Health (EBSCO), Academic search Premier (EBSCO), and Dissertations and Theses (Proquest). The search for literature included dates of database inception through February 2019. **Our search strategy and study selection process is further explained using a modified PRISMA Flow Diagram (not pictured).
Data Analysis. Out of 360 articles, 39 were eligible for review and assessment. Inclusion criteria: articles published in English, discussed pre-doctoral dental student training, awareness, competency for risk assessment, and curriculum content for OPC and its relation to HPV.  Reviewers independently reviewed abstracts, selected articles for inclusion and extracted data.  Discrepancies among reviewers were resolved by consensus characterization.  
Results. In this preliminary study we focused on mapping the nature and volume of the existing literature rather than an answer to a question; but these findings present a significant educational training opportunity for dental students with respect to their understanding and detection of OPC and HPV.  We identified 12 studies that examined discussed pre-doctoral dental student training, awareness, competency for risk assessment, and curriculum content for OPC and its relation to HPV. Five studies described pre-doctoral dental students’ ability to deliver patient education about OPC and its relation to HPV.  Most studies involved the examination of pre-doctoral dental students’ awareness of HPV and OPC connection (n=12) and readiness to assess risks for OPC (n=11).  Studies that described content developed or existing content utilized within their programs were rare (n=3) and but did demonstrate adoptions of curriculum content within pre-doctoral training.  Although the majority of publications within this study state the need for HPV and OPC training and curriculum inclusion for pre-doctoral dental students, there is limited published literature on this content. Future analysis should include survey assessment of pre-doctoral dental training programs efforts for enhancing student efficacy and awareness for HPV-related OPC.
Conclusions. Future dental curricula should include understanding risks for HPV and OPC, conducting relevant assessments for OPC and HPV risks and behaviors, communication techniques in patient health education as well as training to empower preceptors and/or clinical faculty. Implementation of curricula with such learning competencies presents a unique opportunity to prepare a dental workforce to increase detection of OPC, awareness of HPV-related oropharyngeal cancer and increase vaccination rates against HPV.
